    "texts":[
        {
            "texttype":"Online",
            "textpurpose":"Gallery Label",
            "textentryhtml":"This unusual representation of Mt. Fuji is composed of the poems of ancient courtiers and emperors. The detail of the painting at right illustrates how tiny kana script forms the image of Mt. Fuji. Shido was a literary scholar and historian particularly involved in the study of native traditions of Japan. He taught Japanese classics to nobles who served at the imperial court in Kyoto and worked as a tutor to Emperor Ninko. Shido composed this work on the New Year of 1842, the same year he died.",
            "remarks":null
        },
        {
            "texttype":"Online",
            "textpurpose":"Gallery Label",
            "textentryhtml":"\r\nThis unusual representation of Mount Fuji is composed of poems written by ancient courtiers and emperors. This textbook exercise in the word-image genre was written by Shidō on New Year’s Day of 1842, the very year he passed away at the age of seventy-eight. He was still sprightly at this point, judging from the miniature writing and the joking claim that he had no need of glasses.</P></SPAN>",
            "remarks":"The Art of Calligraphy in Asia Rotation"
        },
        {
